<p>The <b>regular icosahedron</b> (or simply icosahedron) is a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convex_polyhedron" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Convex polyhedron">convex polyhedron</a> that can be constructed from <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagonal_antiprism" title=3D"Pent=
agonal antiprism">pentagonal antiprism</a> by attaching two <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagonal_pyramid" title=3D"Pentagonal pyramid">=
pentagonal pyramids</a> with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regul=
ar_polygon" title=3D"Regular polygon">regular faces</a> to each of its pent=
agonal faces, or by putting points onto the cube. The resulting polyhedron =
has 20 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equilateral_triangle" title=
=3D"Equilateral triangle">equilateral triangles</a> as its faces, 30 edges,=
 and 12 vertices. It is an example of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Platonic_solid" title=3D"Platonic solid">Platonic solid</a> and of a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deltahedron" title=3D"Deltahedron"=
>deltahedron</a>. The icosahedral graph represents the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skeleton_(topology)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sk=
eleton (topology)">skeleton</a> of a regular icosahedron.
</p><p>Many polyhedra and other related figures are constructed from the re=
gular icosahedron, including its 59 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Stellation" title=3D"Stellation">stellations</a>. The <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_dodecahedron" title=3D"Great dodecahedron">grea=
t dodecahedron</a>, one of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kep=
ler%E2%80%93Poinsot_polyhedra" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kepler=E2=80=
=93Poinsot polyhedra">Kepler=E2=80=93Poinsot polyhedra</a>, is constructed =
by either stellation of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regula=
r_dodecahedron" title=3D"Regular dodecahedron">regular dodecahedron</a> or =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faceting" title=3D"Faceting">facet=
ing</a> of the icosahedron. Some of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Johnson_solid" title=3D"Johnson solid">Johnson solids</a> can be cons=
tructed by removing the pentagonal pyramids. The regular icosahedron's <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_polyhedron" title=3D"Dual polyhed=
ron">dual polyhedron</a> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Re=
gular_dodecahedron" title=3D"Regular dodecahedron">regular dodecahedron</a>=
, and their relation has a historical background in the comparison mensurat=
ion. It is analogous to a four-dimensional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Polytope" title=3D"Polytope">polytope</a>, the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/600-cell" title=3D"600-cell">600-cell</a>.
</p><p>Regular icosahedra can be found in nature; a well-known example is t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capsid" title=3D"Capsid">capsid=
</a> in biology. Other applications of the regular icosahedron are the usag=
e of its net in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cartography" title=
=3D"Cartography">cartography</a>, and the twenty-sided dice that may have b=
een used in ancient times but are now <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/D20_System" title=3D"D20 System">commonplace in modern</a> <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tabletop_role-playing_games" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Tabletop role-playing games">tabletop role-playing games</a>.
</p>
