<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Construction">Construction<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_icos=
ahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Construct=
ion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>The regular icosahedron is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ic=
osahedron" title=3D"Icosahedron">twenty-sided polyhedron</a> wherein the fa=
ces are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equilateral_triangle" titl=
e=3D"Equilateral triangle">equilateral triangles</a>. It is one of the eigh=
t convex <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deltahedra" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Deltahedra">deltahedra</a>, a polyhedron wherein all of i=
ts faces are equilateral triangles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-1=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> Variously, it can be constructed as follows:
</p>
<ul><li>Started by attaching two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
entagonal_pyramid" title=3D"Pentagonal pyramid">pentagonal pyramids</a> wit=
h <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polygon" title=3D"Regula=
r polygon">regular faces</a> to the base of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Pentagonal_antiprism" title=3D"Pentagonal antiprism">pentagonal=
 antiprism</a>. These components are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Elementary_polyhedron" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Elementary polyhed=
ron">elementaries</a>=E2=80=94they cannot be disintegrated into smaller con=
vex polyhedra with regular faces again. Replacing bases of a pentagonal ant=
iprism with ten triangular pyramids,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-=
2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> the regular icosahedron is classified as a composite polyhedr=
on, the opposite of an elementary polyhedron.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTETi=
mofeenko2010_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTETimofeenko2010-3"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This=
 construction led to the alternative names called <b>bicapped pentagonal an=
tiprism</b>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKing2020_4-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTN=
OTEKing2020-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> or <b>gyroelongated pentagonal bipyramid</b> due =
to its construction process through <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Gyroelongation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gyroelongation">gyroelonga=
tion</a>=E2=80=94polyhedra construction by attaching two pyramids onto the =
base of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antiprism" title=3D"Ant=
iprism">antiprism</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGailiunas2023339_5-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedr=
on#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGailiunas2023339-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Icosahedron-golden-rectangles=
.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9c/Icosahedron-golden-rectangles.svg/250px-Icos=
ahedron-golden-rectangles.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"232" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"500" data-file-height=
=3D"463"></a><figcaption>Three mutually perpendicular <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_rectangle" title=3D"Golden rectangle">golden rec=
tangles</a>, with edges connecting their corners, form a regular icosahedro=
n.</figcaption></figure>
<ul><li>The twelve vertices of a regular icosahedron describe the three mut=
ually perpendicular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_rectang=
le" title=3D"Golden rectangle">golden rectangular planes</a>, whose corners=
 are connected. These rectangular planes can be constructed from a pair of =
vertices located on the midpoints of the opposite edges on a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cube" title=3D"Cube">cube</a>'s surface, drawing=
 a segment line between those two, and divides the segment line in a <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio" title=3D"Golden ratio">gol=
den ratio</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><spa=
n class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: n=
one;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displ=
aystyle \varphi =3D(1+{\sqrt {5}})/2}">
