</p><p>A problem dating back to the ancient Greeks is determining which of =
two shapes has a larger volume: a regular icosahedron inscribed in a sphere=
, or a regular dodecahedron inscribed in the same sphere. The problem was s=
olved by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hero_of_Alexandria" title=
=3D"Hero of Alexandria">Hero</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Pappus_of_Alexandria" title=3D"Pappus of Alexandria">Pappus</a>, and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci" title=3D"Fibonacci">Fibonacci=
</a>, among others.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHerz-Fischler2013[httpsbooks=
googlecombooksidaYjXZJwLARQCpgPA138_138=E2=80=93140]_13-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-=
FOOTNOTEHerz-Fischler2013[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidaYjXZJwLARQCpgPA138_138=
%E2%80%93140]-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apol=
lonius_of_Perga" title=3D"Apollonius of Perga">Apollonius of Perga</a> disc=
overed the curious result that the ratio of volumes of these two shapes is =
the same as the ratio of their surface areas.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESi=
mmons2007[httpsbooksgooglecombooksid3KOst4Mon90CpgPA50_50]_14-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite=
_note-FOOTNOTESimmons2007[httpsbooksgooglecombooksid3KOst4Mon90CpgPA50_50]-=
14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Both volumes have formulas involving the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio" title=3D"Golden ratio">golden ratio</a=
>, but taken to different powers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESutton2002[htt=
psbooksgooglecombooksidvgo7bTxDmIsCpgPA55_55]_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOT=
ESutton2002[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidvgo7bTxDmIsCpgPA55_55]-15"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> As it turns out, the regular icosahedron occupies less of the sphere's vo=
lume (60.54%) than the regular dodecahedron (66.49%).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icos=
ahedron#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
