t" data-file-width=3D"816" data-file-height=3D"824"></a><figcaption>Illustr=
ation of an icosahedral symmetry. The five-fold, three-fold, and two-fold a=
re labeled in blue, red, and magenta, respectively. The mirror planes are t=
he cyan <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_circle" title=3D"Gre=
at circle">great circles</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The regular icosahedron has the thirty-one axes of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotational_symmetry" title=3D"Rotational symmetry">rota=
tional symmetry</a> (that is, rotating around an axis that results in an id=
entical appearance). There are six axes passing through two opposite vertic=
es, ten axes rotating a triangular face, and fifteen axes passing through a=
ny of its edges. Respectively, these axes are five-fold rotational symmetry=
 (0=C2=B0, 72=C2=B0, 144=C2=B0, 216=C2=B0, and 288=C2=B0), three-fold rotat=
ional symmetry (0=C2=B0, 120=C2=B0, and 240=C2=B0), and two-fold rotational=
 symmetry (0=C2=B0 and 180=C2=B0).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-1=
9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> The regular icosahedron also has fifteen mirror planes that =
can be represented as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_circle=
" title=3D"Great circle">great circles</a> on a sphere. It divides the surf=
ace of a sphere into 120 triangles <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Fundamental_domain" title=3D"Fundamental domain">fundamental domains</a>; =
these triangles are called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mobius_=
triangle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mobius triangle">Mobius triangles<=
/a>. Both reflections and rotational symmetries are the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isometry" title=3D"Isometry">isometries</a>=E2=80=94t=
ransformations in order to maintain the appearance=E2=80=94which forms the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Full_icosahedral_symmetry" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Full icosahedral symmetry">full icosahedral symme=
try</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \mathrm {I} _{\mathrm {h} }}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">I</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">h</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathrm {I} _=
{\mathrm {h} }}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/a9fdfce71bda597451d015e732f835e6fc14b348" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:1.986ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ma=
thrm {I} _{\mathrm {h} }}"></span> of order 120.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOT=
EHart1998196_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHart1998196-20"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This=
 symmetry group is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_isomorphi=
sm" title=3D"Group isomorphism">isomorphic</a> to the product of the rotati=
onal symmetry group and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclic=
_group" title=3D"Cyclic group">cyclic group</a> of size two, generated by t=
he reflection through the center of the regular icosahedron.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-FOOTNOTESeidel1991[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidbrziBQAAQBAJpgPA364_364]_=
21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_=
icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTESeidel1991[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidbrziBQAA=
QBAJpgPA364_364]-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The rotational <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetry_gro=
up" title=3D"Symmetry group">symmetry group</a> of the regular icosahedron =
is isomorphic to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternating_g=
roup" title=3D"Alternating group">alternating group</a> on five letters. Th=
is non-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abelian_group" title=3D"Abe=
lian group">abelian</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simple_gro=
up" title=3D"Simple group">simple group</a> is the only non-trivial <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_subgroup" title=3D"Normal subgroup=
">normal subgroup</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symme=
tric_group" title=3D"Symmetric group">symmetric group</a> on five letters.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGray2018[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidgl1oDwAAQBAJp=
gPA371_371]_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGray2018[httpsbooksgooglecombooks=
idgl1oDwAAQBAJpgPA371_371]-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Since the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Galois_group" title=3D"Galois group">Galois group</a> of=
 the general <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quintic_equation" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quintic equation">quintic equation</a> is isomo=
rphic to the symmetric group on five letters, and this normal subgroup is s=
imple and non-abelian, the general quintic equation does not have a solutio=
n in radicals. The proof of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ab=
el%E2%80%93Ruffini_theorem" title=3D"Abel=E2=80=93Ruffini theorem">Abel=E2=
=80=93Ruffini theorem</a> uses this simple fact,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOT=
ERotman1998[httpsbooksgooglecombooksid0kHhBwAAQBAJpgPA75_74=E2=80=9375]_23-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_ico=
sahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTERotman1998[httpsbooksgooglecombooksid0kHhBwAAQBA=
JpgPA75_74%E2%80%9375]-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Felix_Klein" title=3D"Felix Klein">Felix Klein</a> wrote a book th=
at made use of the theory of icosahedral symmetries to derive an analytical=
 solution to the general quintic equation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cit=
e_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The regular icosahedron is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Isogonal_figure" title=3D"Isogonal figure">isogonal</a>, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isohedral" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Isohedral"=
>isohedral</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isotoxal" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Isotoxal">isotoxal</a>: any two vertices, two fa=
ces, and two edges of a regular icosahedron can be transformed by rotations=
 and reflections under its symmetry orbit, which preserves the appearance. =
Each regular polyhedron has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conv=
ex_hull" title=3D"Convex hull">convex hull</a> on its edge midpoints; <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icosidodecahedron" title=3D"Icosidodeca=
hedron">icosidodecahedron</a> is the convex hull of a regular icosahedron.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESenechal1989[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidOToVjZW9C=
KMCpgPA12_12]_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTESenechal1989[httpsbooksgoogleco=
mbooksidOToVjZW9CKMCpgPA12_12]-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Each vertex is surrounded by=
 five equilateral triangles, so the regular icosahedron denotes <span class=
