max-width:142px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:143px;overflow:h=
idden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fi=
le:ScatDice.JPG" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https:/=
/upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b2/ScatDice.JPG/250px-ScatD=
ice.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"140" height=3D"144" class=3D"mw-file-e=
lement" data-file-width=3D"322" data-file-height=3D"331"></a></span></div><=
div class=3D"thumbcaption">The <i>Scattergories</i> twenty-sided die, exclu=
ding the six letters Q, U, V, X, Y, and Z</div></div></div></div></div>
<p>Dice are among the most common objects that utilize different polyhedra,=
 one of which is the regular icosahedron. The twenty-sided die was found in=
 ancient times. One example is the die from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Ptolemaic_Egypt" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ptolemaic Egypt">=
Ptolemaic Egypt</a>, which was later used with Greek letters inscribed on t=
he faces in the period of Greece and Rome.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cit=
e_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
Another example was found in the treasure of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Tipu_Sultan" title=3D"Tipu Sultan">Tipu Sultan</a>, which was ma=
de out of gold and with numbers written on each face.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FO=
OTNOTECromwell1997[httpsarchiveorgdetailspolyhedra0000crompage4mode1upviewt=
heater_4]_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECromwell1997[httpsarchiveorgdetails=
polyhedra0000crompage4mode1upviewtheater_4]-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In several <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roleplaying_game=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Roleplaying game">roleplaying games</a>, s=
uch as <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dungeons_%26_Dragons" ti=
tle=3D"Dungeons &amp; Dragons">Dungeons &amp; Dragons</a></i>, the twenty-s=
ided die (labeled as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dice#Polyhedr=
al_dice" title=3D"Dice">d20</a>) is commonly used in determining success or=
 failure of an action. It may be numbered from "0" to "9" twice, in which f=
orm it usually serves as a ten-sided die (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Dice#Non-cubical_dice" title=3D"Dice">d10</a>); most modern version=
s are labeled from "1" to "20".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-29">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scattergories" titl=
e=3D"Scattergories">Scattergories</a></i> is another board game in which th=
e player names the category entries on a card within a given set time. The =
naming of such categories is initially with the letters contained in every =
twenty-sided dice.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFlanaganGregory2015[httpsbook=
sgooglecombooksidhViuEAAAQBAJpgPA85_85]_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFla=
naganGregory2015[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidhViuEAAAQBAJpgPA85_85]-30"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Natural_forms_and_sciences"=
