ss=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:236px;max-width:236px"><div class=3D"thumbima=
ge" style=3D"height:110px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Dymaxion_projection.png" class=3D"mw=
-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipe=
dia/commons/thumb/5/53/Dymaxion_projection.png/250px-Dymaxion_projection.pn=
g" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"234" height=3D"111" class=3D"mw-file-element=
" data-file-width=3D"2180" data-file-height=3D"1030"></a></span></div><div =
class=3D"thumbcaption"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dymaxion_ma=
p" title=3D"Dymaxion map">Dymaxion map</a>, created by the net of a regular=
 icosahedron</div></div></div></div></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virology" title=3D"Virology"=
>virology</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herpesviridae" titl=
e=3D"Herpesviridae">herpes virus</a> have icosahedral <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capsid" title=3D"Capsid">shells</a>, especially well-kn=
own in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adenovirus" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Adenovirus">adenovirus</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGall=
ardoP=C3=A9rez-IllanaMart=C3=ADn-Gonz=C3=A1lezSan_Mart=C3=ADn2021_31-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedr=
on#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGallardoP%C3%A9rez-IllanaMart%C3%ADn-Gonz%C3%A1lezSan_=
Mart%C3%ADn2021-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The outer protein shell of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HIV" title=3D"HIV">HIV</a> is enclosed in a regula=
r icosahedron, as is the head of a typical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Myovirus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Myovirus">myovirus</a>.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEStraussStrauss200835=E2=80=9362_32-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_=
note-FOOTNOTEStraussStrauss200835%E2%80%9362-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Several specie=
s of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radiolarian" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Radiolarian">radiolarians</a> discovered by <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernst_Haeckel" title=3D"Ernst Haeckel">Ernst Haeck=
el</a>, described their shells as like-shaped various regular polyhedra; on=
e of which is <i>Circogonia icosahedra</i>, whose skeleton is shaped like a=
 regular icosahedron.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-33"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>In chemistry, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closo_clu=
ster" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Closo cluster">closo</a>-<a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carboranes" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Carb=
oranes">carboranes</a> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemica=
l_compound" title=3D"Chemical compound">compounds</a> with a shape resembli=
ng the regular icosahedron.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESpokoyny2013_34-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahe=
dron#cite_note-FOOTNOTESpokoyny2013-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_twinning" title=3D"Crystal twinning">crystal =
twinning</a> with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icosahedral_twin=
s" title=3D"Icosahedral twins">icosahedral shapes</a> also occurs in crysta=
ls, especially <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nanoparticle" title=
=3D"Nanoparticle">nanoparticles</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHofmeister2=
004_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regu=
lar_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHofmeister2004-35"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Many <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_structure_of_boron-rich_metal_b=
orides" title=3D"Crystal structure of boron-rich metal borides">borides</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allotropes_of_boron" title=3D=
"Allotropes of boron">allotropes of boron</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allotropes_of_boron#%CE%B1-rhombohedral_boron" title=3D=
"Allotropes of boron">=CE=B1-</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Allotropes_of_boron#%CE%B2-rhombohedral_boron" title=3D"Allotropes of b=
oron">=CE=B2-rhombohedral</a> contain boron B<sub>12</sub> icosahedron as a=
 basic structure unit.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDronskowskiKikkawaStein20=
17[httpsbooksgooglecombookside0VBDwAAQBAJpgPA436_435=E2=80=93436]_36-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedr=
on#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDronskowskiKikkawaStein2017[httpsbooksgooglecombooksid=
e0VBDwAAQBAJpgPA436_435%E2%80%93436]-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In cartography, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R._Buckmins=
ter_Fuller" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"R. Buckminster Fuller">R. Buckmi=
nster Fuller</a> used the net of a regular icosahedron to create a map know=
n as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dymaxion_map" title=3D"Dymaxi=
on map">Dymaxion map</a>, by subdividing the net into triangles, followed b=
y calculating the grid on the Earth's surface, and transferring the results=
 from the sphere to the polyhedron. This projection was created during the =
time that Fuller realized that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gre=
enland" title=3D"Greenland">Greenland</a> is smaller than <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_America" title=3D"South America">South Americ=
a</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECromwell1997[httpsarchiveorgdetailspolyhe=
dra0000crompage7mode1upviewtheater_7]_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECromwel=
l1997[httpsarchiveorgdetailspolyhedra0000crompage7mode1upviewtheater_7]-37"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomson_problem" tit=
le=3D"Thomson problem">Thomson problem</a>, concerning the minimum-energy c=
onfiguration of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><s=
pan class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display:=
 none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\dis=
playstyle n}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>n</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle n}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/a601995d55609f2d9f5e233e36fbe9ea26011b3b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.395ex; height:1.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle n}"=
></span> charged particles on a sphere, and for the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Tammes_problem" title=3D"Tammes problem">Tammes problem</=
a> of constructing a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_cod=
e" title=3D"Spherical code">spherical code</a> maximizing the smallest dist=
ance among the points, the minimum solution known for <span class=3D"mwe-ma=
th-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline m=
we-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.=
org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle n=3D12}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>n</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>12</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle n=3D12}</anno=
tation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/38fb7dfd38b5db65d78bb6f2c1bf9e6e6cd07c14" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:6.818ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle n=
=3D12}"></span> places the points at the vertices of a regular icosahedron,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circumscribed_sphere" title=3D"Ci=
rcumscribed sphere">inscribed in a sphere</a>. This configuration is proven=
 optimal for the Tammes problem, and also for the Thomas problem.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In tensegrity, the regular icosahedron is composed of six struts and=
 twenty-four cables that connect twelve nodes. One self-stress state is pre=
sent within the combination achieved through the use of cellular <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morphogenesis" title=3D"Morphogenesis">morph=
ogenesis</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAloui_et_al.2019_39-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_=
note-FOOTNOTEAloui_et_al.2019-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ancient_texts">Ancient text=
s</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_ic=
osahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Ancien=
t texts"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1273380762/mw-parser-output/.tmulti"><div class=3D"thumb tmulti tright"><di=
v class=3D"thumbinner multiimageinner" style=3D"width:292px;max-width:292px=
"><div class=3D"trow"><div class=3D"tsingle" style=3D"width:151px;max-width=
:151px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"height:159px;overflow:hidden"><s=
pan typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Kepler=
_Icosahedron_Water.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"=
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Kepler_Icosahedro=
n_Water.jpg/250px-Kepler_Icosahedron_Water.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D=
"149" height=3D"160" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"306" data=
-file-height=3D"328"></a></span></div><div class=3D"thumbcaption">Sketch of=
 a regular icosahedron by Johannes Kepler</div></div><div class=3D"tsingle"=
 style=3D"width:137px;max-width:137px"><div class=3D"thumbimage" style=3D"h=
eight:159px;overflow:hidden"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mysterium_Cosmographicum_solar_system_model.jpg" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-description"><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.=
org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/33/Mysterium_Cosmographicum_solar_system_mode=
l.jpg/250px-Mysterium_Cosmographicum_solar_system_model.jpg" decoding=3D"as=
ync" width=3D"135" height=3D"159" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"3252" data-file-height=3D"3832"></a></span></div><div class=3D"thumbcap=
tion"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_Kepler" title=3D"Jo=
hannes Kepler">Kepler's</a> Platonic solid model of the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_System" title=3D"Solar System">Solar System</a>=
</div></div></div></div></div>
<p>The regular icosahedron is one of the five <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Platonic_solid" title=3D"Platonic solid">Platonic solids</a>. T=
he regular polyhedra have been known since antiquity, but are named after <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plato" title=3D"Plato">Plato</a> wh=
o, in his <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timaeus_(dialogue)" titl=
e=3D"Timaeus (dialogue)"><i>Timaeus</i></a> dialogue, identified these with=
 the five <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_elements" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Classical elements">elements</a>, whose elementa=
ry units were attributed these shapes: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Fire_(classical_element)" title=3D"Fire (classical element)">fire</a> =
(tetrahedron), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air_(classical_elem=
ent)" title=3D"Air (classical element)">air</a> (octahedron), <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water_(classical_element)" title=3D"Water (clas=
sical element)">water</a> (icosahedron), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Earth_(classical_element)" title=3D"Earth (classical element)">earth=
</a> (cube) and the shape of the universe as a whole (dodecahedron). <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a>'s <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid=
's Elements"><i>Elements</i></a> defined the Platonic solids and solved the=
 problem of finding the ratio of the circumscribed sphere's diameter to the=
 edge length.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHeath1908262,_478,_480_40-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron=
#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHeath1908262,_478,_480-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Following their identification with the elements by Plato, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_Kepler" title=3D"Johannes Kepler=
">Johannes Kepler</a> in his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ha=
rmonices_Mundi" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Harmonices Mundi">Harmonices=
 Mundi</a></i> sketched each of them, in particular, the regular icosahedro=
n.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECromwell1997[httpsarchiveorgdetailspolyhedra0=
000crompage55_55]_41-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECromwell1997[httpsarchiveor=
gdetailspolyhedra0000crompage55_55]-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In his <i><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mysterium_Cosmographicum" title=3D"Mysterium Co=
smographicum">Mysterium Cosmographicum</a></i>, he also proposed a model of=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_System" title=3D"Solar =
System">Solar System</a> based on the placement of Platonic solids in a con=
centric sequence of increasing radius of the inscribed and circumscribed sp=
heres whose radii gave the distance of the six known planets from the commo=
n center. The ordering of the solids, from innermost to outermost, consiste=
d of: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_octahedron" title=3D=
"Regular octahedron">regular octahedron</a>, regular icosahedron, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron" title=3D"Regular do=
decahedron">regular dodecahedron</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Regular_tetrahedron" title=3D"Regular tetrahedron">regular tetrahedron<=
/a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cube" title=3D"Cube">cube=
</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2003147_42-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOT=
ELivio2003147-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonardo_da_Vinci" title=3D=
"Leonardo da Vinci">Leonardo da Vinci</a>'s <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Divina_proportione" title=3D"Divina proportione">Divina propor=
tione</a></i> drew both regular icosahedron and dodecahedron.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-FOOTNOTEHart1998195_43-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHart1998195-43"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Representation">Representat=
ion</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_=
icosahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Repr=
esentation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"As_a_graph">As a graph</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_icosahed=
ron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: As a graph">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Icosahedron_graph.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/8/83/Icosahedron_graph.svg/250px-Icosahedron_graph.svg.png" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"234" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"625" data-file-height=3D"584"></a><figcaption>Icosahedral=
 graph</figcaption></figure>
<p>Every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Platonic_graph" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Platonic graph">Platonic graph</a>, including the <b>=
icosahedral graph</b>, is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyhe=
dral_graph" title=3D"Polyhedral graph">polyhedral graph</a>: they <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planar_graph" title=3D"Planar graph">can =
be drawn in the plane without crossing its edges</a>, and <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K-vertex-connected_graph" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"K-vertex-connected graph">the removal of any two of its vertices leav=
es a connected subgraph</a>. According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Steinitz%27s_theorem" title=3D"Steinitz's theorem">Steinitz's theor=
em</a>, the icosahedral graph endowed with these heretofore properties repr=
esents the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skeleton_(topology)" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Skeleton (topology)">skeleton</a> of a regular=
 icosahedron.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBickle2020[httpsbooksgooglecombook=
sid2sbVDwAAQBAJpgPA147_147]_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBickle2020[httpsb=
ooksgooglecombooksid2sbVDwAAQBAJpgPA147_147]-44"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The icosahedral graph has twelve vertices, the same number of vertic=
es as a regular icosahedron. These vertices are connected by five edges fro=
m each vertex, making the icosahedral graph <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Regular_graph" title=3D"Regular graph">5-regular</a>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-FOOTNOTEFallatHogben2014[httpsbooksgooglecombooksid8hnYCwAAQBAJpgSA=
46-PA29_29]Section_46_45-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFallatHogben2014[httpsb=
ooksgooglecombooksid8hnYCwAAQBAJpgSA46-PA29_29]Section_46-45"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The icosahedral graph is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamilton=
ian_graph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hamiltonian graph">Hamiltonian</a=
>, because it has a cycle that can visit each vertex exactly once.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHopkins2004_46-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHopkins2004-=
46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Any subset of four vertices has three connected edges, with=
 one being the central of all of those three, and the icosahedral graph has=
 no <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Induced_subgraph" title=3D"Ind=
uced subgraph">induced subgraph</a>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Claw-free_graph" title=3D"Claw-free graph">claw-free graph</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEChudnovskySeymour2005_47-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECh=
udnovskySeymour2005-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The icosahedral graph is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Graceful_graph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Graceful graph">graceful gra=
ph</a>, meaning that each vertex can be labeled with an <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integer</a> between 0 and =
30 inclusive, in such a way that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Absolute_difference" title=3D"Absolute difference">absolute difference</=
a> between the labels of an edge's two vertices is different for every edge=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGallian1998_48-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGal=
lian1998-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"As_a_configuration_matrix">=
As a configuration matrix</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DRegular_icosahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=
=3D"Edit section: As a configuration matrix"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The regular icosahedron can be represented as a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Platonic_solid#As_a_configuration" title=3D"Platonic solid=
">configuration matrix</a>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matr=
ix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">matrix</a> in which the ro=
ws and columns correspond to the elements of a polyhedron as the vertices, =
edges, and faces. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_diagona=
l" title=3D"Main diagonal">diagonal</a> of a matrix denotes the number of e=
ach element that appears in a polyhedron, whereas the non-diagonal of a mat=
rix denotes the number of the column's elements that occur in or at the row=
's element. The following matrix is:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECoxeter1973=
sec_1.8_Configurations_49-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECoxeter1973sec_1.8_Con=
figurations-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle {\begin{bmatrix}12&amp;5&amp;5\\2&amp;30&amp;2\\3&amp;3&amp;20\=
end{bmatrix}}.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow>
            <mo>[</mo>
            <mtable rowspacing=3D"4pt" columnspacing=3D"1em">
              <mtr>
                <mtd>
                  <mn>12</mn>
                </mtd>
                <mtd>
                  <mn>5</mn>
                </mtd>
                <mtd>
                  <mn>5</mn>
                </mtd>
              </mtr>
              <mtr>
                <mtd>
                  <mn>2</mn>
                </mtd>
                <mtd>
                  <mn>30</mn>
                </mtd>
                <mtd>
                  <mn>2</mn>
                </mtd>
              </mtr>
              <mtr>
                <mtd>
                  <mn>3</mn>
                </mtd>
                <mtd>
                  <mn>3</mn>
                </mtd>
                <mtd>
                  <mn>20</mn>
                </mtd>
              </mtr>
            </mtable>
            <mo>]</mo>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\begin{bmatr=
ix}12&amp;5&amp;5\\2&amp;30&amp;2\\3&amp;3&amp;20\end{bmatrix}}.}</annotati=
on>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/7f9b6a74ecd8b52bcd738e4b02a0b524f9c9bbda" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -4.005ex; width:16.119ex; height:9.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {=
\begin{bmatrix}12&amp;5&amp;5\\2&amp;30&amp;2\\3&amp;3&amp;20\end{bmatrix}}=
.}"></span>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Related_figures">Related fi=
gures</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegula=
r_icosahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Re=
lated figures"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Inscribed_in_other_Platonic=
_solids">Inscribed in other Platonic solids</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_icosahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;s=
ection=3D15" title=3D"Edit section: Inscribed in other Platonic solids"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>The regular icosahedron is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Dual_polyhedron" title=3D"Dual polyhedron">dual polyhedron</a> of the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron" title=3D"Regular =
dodecahedron">regular dodecahedron</a>. A regular icosahedron can be inscri=
bed in a regular dodecahedron by placing its vertices at the face centers o=
f the regular dodecahedron, and vice versa. The regular dodecahedron has ic=
osahedral symmetry.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-50"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Apart from the construction above, the regular icosahedron can be in=
scribed in a regular octahedron by placing its twelve vertices on the twelv=
e edges of the octahedron such that they divide each edge in the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_section" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Golden section">golden section</a>. Because the resulting segments are =
unequal, there are five different ways to do this consistently, so five dis=
joint icosahedra can be inscribed in each octahedron.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FO=
OTNOTECoxeterdu_ValFlatherPetrie19384_51-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECoxeter=
du_ValFlatherPetrie19384-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Another relation between the two i=
s that they are part of the progressive transformation from the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cuboctahedron" title=3D"Cuboctahedron">cuboct=
ahedron</a>'s rigid struts and flexible vertices, known as <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jitterbug_transformation" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Jitterbug transformation">jitterbug transformation</a>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-FOOTNOTEVerheyen1989_52-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVerheyen1989-52">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>A regular icosahedron of edge length <span class=3D"mwe-math-element=
 mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-ma=
thml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/M=
ath/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle 1/\varphi \approx 0.618}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>=CF=86<!-- =CF=86 --></mi>
        <mo>=E2=89=88<!-- =E2=89=88 --></mo>
        <mn>0.618</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle 1/\varphi \ap=
prox 0.618}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ee2956736e09abd4c4d71925d61a4979d14025d2" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:12.24ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle 1/\=
varphi \approx 0.618}"></span> can be inscribed in a unit-edge-length cube =
by placing six of its edges=E2=80=94three orthogonal opposite pairs=E2=80=
=94on the square faces of the cube, centered on the face centers and parall=
el or perpendicular to the square's edges.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBorov=
ik20068=E2=80=939=C2=A75._How_to_draw_an_icosahedron_on_a_blackboard_53-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosah=
edron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBorovik20068%E2%80%939%C2%A75._How_to_draw_an_icosa=
hedron_on_a_blackboard-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Because there are five times as many=
 icosahedron edges as cube faces, there are five ways to do this consistent=
ly, so five disjoint icosahedra can be inscribed in each cube. The edge len=
gths of the cube and the inscribed icosahedron are in the golden ratio.<sup=
 class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowra=
p;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed"=
 title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs refere=
nces to reliable sources. (August 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</s=
up>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Stellations">Stellations</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_icosah=
edron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Stellation=
s"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fifty-Nine_Icosahedra" title=
=3D"The Fifty-Nine Icosahedra">The Fifty-Nine Icosahedra</a></div>
<p>The regular icosahedron has a large number of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Stellation" title=3D"Stellation">stellations</a>, constructe=
d by extending the faces of a regular icosahedron. <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#CITEREFCoxeterdu_ValFlatherPetrie1938"=
>Coxeter et al. (1938)</a> in their work, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/The_Fifty-Nine_Icosahedra" title=3D"The Fifty-Nine Icosahedra">T=
he Fifty-Nine Icosahedra</a></i>, identified fifty-nine stellations for the=
 regular icosahedron. The regular icosahedron itself is the zeroth stellati=
on of an icosahedron, and the first stellation has each original face augme=
nted by a low pyramid. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Final_s=
tellation_of_the_icosahedron" title=3D"Final stellation of the icosahedron"=
>final stellation</a> includes all of the cells in the icosahedron's stella=
tion diagram, meaning every three intersecting face planes of the icosahedr=
al core intersect either on a vertex of this polyhedron or inside it.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
