<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Faceting">Faceting</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_icosahedron&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Faceting"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_dodecahedron" title=
=3D"Great dodecahedron">great dodecahedron</a> can be constructed from the =
regular icosahedron in other ways. Aside from the stellation, the great dod=
ecahedron can be constructed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fa=
ceting" title=3D"Faceting">faceting</a> the regular icosahedron, that is, r=
emoving the triangle faces of the regular icosahedron without removing the =
vertices or creating a new one; then forming twelve regular pentagons on se=
ts of five vertices inside of a regular icosahedron. These new faces inters=
ect each other, making a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagram=
" title=3D"Pentagram">pentagram</a> as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Vertex_figure" title=3D"Vertex figure">vertex figure</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
