<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triakis_icosahedron" title=
=3D"Triakis icosahedron">triakis icosahedron</a> is a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catalan_solid" title=3D"Catalan solid">Catalan solid</a=
> constructed by attaching the base of triangular pyramids onto each face o=
f a regular icosahedron, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kleet=
ope" title=3D"Kleetope">Kleetope</a> of an icosahedron.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
FOOTNOTEBrigagliaPalladinoVaccaro2018_56-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBrigagl=
iaPalladinoVaccaro2018-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Truncated_icosahedron" title=3D"Truncated icosahedron">truncated i=
cosahedron</a> is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedean_s=
olid" title=3D"Archimedean solid">Archimedean solid</a> constructed by trun=
cating the vertices of a regular icosahedron; the resulting polyhedron may =
be considered as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ball_(associati=
on_football)" title=3D"Ball (association football)">football</a> because of=
 having a pattern of numerous hexagonal and pentagonal faces,<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-57" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regu=
lar_icosahedron#cite_note-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or a structural form of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbon" title=3D"Carbon">carbon</a> known=
 as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buckminsterfullerene" title=3D=
"Buckminsterfullerene">buckminsterfullerene</a> that has 60 carbon atoms bo=
nded together.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKatz2006[httpsbooksgooglecombooks=
idGmQR1tuk5IgCpgPA361_361]_58-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKatz2006[httpsbook=
sgooglecombooksidGmQR1tuk5IgCpgPA361_361]-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>57<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnson_solid" title=3D"J=
ohnson solid">Johnson solid</a> is a polyhedron whose faces are all regular=
 but which is not <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uniform_polyhedr=
on" title=3D"Uniform polyhedron">uniform</a>. In other words, they do not i=
nclude the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedean_solid" titl=
e=3D"Archimedean solid">Archimedean solids</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Catalan_solid" title=3D"Catalan solid">Catalan solids</a>=
, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prism_(geometry)" title=3D"P=
rism (geometry)">prisms</a>, or the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Antiprism" title=3D"Antiprism">antiprisms</a>. Some Johnson solids can be=
 derived by removing part of a regular icosahedron, a process known as <i>d=
iminishment</i>. They are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gyroelon=
gated_pentagonal_pyramid" title=3D"Gyroelongated pentagonal pyramid">gyroel=
ongated pentagonal pyramid</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Me=
tabidiminished_icosahedron" title=3D"Metabidiminished icosahedron">metabidi=
minished icosahedron</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trid=
iminished_icosahedron" title=3D"Tridiminished icosahedron">tridiminished ic=
osahedron</a>, which remove one, two, and three pentagonal pyramids from th=
e icosahedron, respectively.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBerman1971_59-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahed=
ron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBerman1971-59"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5=
8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edge-contracted_icosahe=
dron" title=3D"Edge-contracted icosahedron">edge-contracted icosahedron</a>=
 has a surface like a regular icosahedron but with <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Coplanar" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Coplanar">some fa=
ces lie in the same plane</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTETsuruta2024[https=
booksgooglecombooksidkLckEQAAQBAJpgPA112_112]_60-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOT=
ETsuruta2024[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidkLckEQAAQBAJpgPA112_112]-60"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p>
