<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Spherical_icosahedron"></span>The spherical=
 icosahedron represents a regular icosahedron projected to a sphere, a part=
 of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_polyhedron" title=3D=
"Spherical polyhedron">spherical polyhedron</a>. It can be modeled by the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arc_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Arc (geometry)">arc</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Great_circle" title=3D"Great circle">great circles</a>, creating bound=
s as the edges of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_triang=
le" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Spherical triangle">spherical triangle</=
a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEYackel2013_61-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEYac=
kel2013-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> Identified by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/R._Buckminster_Fuller" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"R. Buckminster Fu=
ller">R. Buckminster Fuller</a>, there are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/31_great_circles_of_the_spherical_icosahedron" title=3D"31 great c=
ircles of the spherical icosahedron">31 great circles in a spherical icosah=
edron</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>61<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Its dual =
is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_dodecahedron" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Spherical dodecahedron">spherical dodecahedron<=
/a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEYackel2013_61-1" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEYa=
ckel2013-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> The appearance of this shape may be found in <i><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impossiball" title=3D"Impossiball">I=
mpossiball</a></i>, a similar toy to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Rubik%27s_Cube" title=3D"Rubik's Cube">Rubik's Cube</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-FOOTNOTEJoyner2008[httpsbooksgooglecombooksid6an_DwAAQBAJpgPA82_82]_63-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_ico=
sahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJoyner2008[httpsbooksgooglecombooksid6an_DwAAQBA=
JpgPA82_82]-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Miscellaneous">Miscellaneou=
s</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_ic=
osahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Miscel=
laneous"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Jessen_icosahedron_with_snub_icosahedron.svg"=
 class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wik=
ipedia/commons/thumb/3/37/Jessen_icosahedron_with_snub_icosahedron.svg/250p=
x-Jessen_icosahedron_with_snub_icosahedron.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" widt=
h=3D"250" height=3D"111" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"911" =
data-file-height=3D"404"></a><figcaption>Regular icosahedron and its non-co=
nvex variant, which differs from Jessen's icosahedron in having different v=
ertex positions and non-right-angled dihedrals</figcaption></figure>
<p>Another related shape can be derived by keeping the vertices of a regula=
r icosahedron in their original positions and replacing certain pairs of eq=
uilateral triangles with pairs of isosceles triangles. The resulting polyhe=
dron has the non-convex version of the regular icosahedron. Nonetheless, it=
 is occasionally incorrectly known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Jessen%27s_icosahedron" title=3D"Jessen's icosahedron">Jessen's icosahe=
dron</a> because of the similar visual, of having the same combinatorial st=
ructure and symmetry as Jessen's icosahedron;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-64" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron=
#cite_note-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> the difference is that the non-convex one does no=
t form a tensegrity structure and does not have right-angled dihedrals.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPugh1976b[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidMcEOfJu3NQACpgP=
A11_11],_[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidMcEOfJu3NQACpgPA26_26]_65-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite=
_note-FOOTNOTEPugh1976b[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidMcEOfJu3NQACpgPA11_11],_[=
httpsbooksgooglecombooksidMcEOfJu3NQACpgPA26_26]-65"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The regular icosahedron is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Four-dimensional_space#Dimensional_analogy" title=3D"Four-dimensional space=
">analogous</a> to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/600-cell" t=
itle=3D"600-cell">600-cell</a>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Regular_4-polytope#Regular_convex_4-polytopes" title=3D"Regular 4-polytope"=
>regular 4-dimensional polytope</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBarnes2012[=
httpsbooksgooglecombooksid7YCUBUd-4BQCpgPA79_79]_66-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOT=
NOTEBarnes2012[httpsbooksgooglecombooksid7YCUBUd-4BQCpgPA79_79]-66"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> This polytope has six hundred regular tetrahedra as its <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Cell (geometry)">cells</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEStillwell2005[httpbo=
oksgooglecombooksidI1QPQic_PxwCpgPA173_173]_67-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTES=
tillwell2005[httpbooksgooglecombooksidI1QPQic_PxwCpgPA173_173]-67"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> The regular icosahedron is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I=
cosahedral_honeycomb" title=3D"Icosahedral honeycomb">cell for the honeycom=
